<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What size water heater do I need?", answer: "The rule of thumb is 1-2 people → 30 gal, 2-3 people → 40 gal, 3-4 people → 50 gal, 4+ people → 75 or 80 gal. But the better measure is peak-hour demand: add up gallons used in your busiest hour of the day and match it to the water heater's First-Hour Rating (FHR), which you can find on the EnergyGuide label. A 40 gallon tank with a 65 gallon FHR handles more than a 50 gallon tank with a 55 gallon FHR." },
  { question: "Tank vs tankless?", answer: "Tank water heaters are cheaper (500 to 1,500 dollars installed) and easier to replace. They run out of hot water after sustained use and waste energy keeping 40-50 gallons hot 24/7. Tankless is 2,000 to 4,500 dollars installed but never runs out, lasts twice as long (20+ years), and cuts water heating energy by 20 to 30 percent. Tankless needs a properly sized gas line or 240V electric circuit — upgrading those can add 500 to 1,500 dollars to installation. For most households, a high-efficiency tank is the best cost-value choice unless you need the endless hot water." },
  { question: "What's the First-Hour Rating?", answer: "FHR is the gallons of hot water a tank can supply in the first hour of use, starting full. It's a combination of tank capacity and recovery rate (how fast the element or burner can reheat cold water). A 50 gallon tank with a fast gas burner might have an FHR of 85; a 50 gallon electric tank might have only 60 because electric recovers more slowly. FHR is more important than tank size for matching real-world peak demand." },
  { question: "How many GPM for a tankless water heater?", answer: "A tankless needs enough flow to serve the simultaneous fixtures running in your peak minute. Assume one shower (2.5 GPM) plus one other fixture (sink at 1.5 GPM, or dishwasher at 1.5 GPM) = 4 GPM minimum. For a 3+ bathroom home, plan on 5 to 7 GPM. For a 4+ bathroom home with laundry and dishwasher running simultaneously, 7 to 9 GPM. In cold climates, the same tankless has a lower effective GPM because incoming water is colder and needs more heat rise." },
  { question: "Is electric or gas water heater better?", answer: "Gas is cheaper to operate in most US markets (roughly half the monthly cost of electric) and recovers faster, but costs 300 to 500 dollars more to install due to venting. Electric is cheaper upfront, quieter, and safer (no combustion), but slower to recover and more expensive to run. Heat pump water heaters are electric with 2-3x efficiency of standard electric and have become competitive with gas for total cost of ownership, especially with federal tax credits." }
]) %>

